<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-03-23T09:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-03-23T09:30:00-05:00" n="279" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d279">
                            <head>279. Memorandum of a Conversation, Mid-Ocean Club, Bermuda, March
                                23, 1957,10:30 a.m.<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d279fn1">Source: Department of State, Conference Files: Lot 62 D 181, CF
                                    868. Secret. Drafted by Fraser Wilkins (<gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss>) on March 25 and circulated to appropriate U.S.
                                    officials.</note></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left"><gloss target="#t_USDel1">USDel</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_MC1">MC</gloss>/8</seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><hi rend="italic"><placeName>Bermuda</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1957-03-23T10:30:00-04:00">March 23, 1957, 10:30
                                            a.m.</date></hi></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <list type="participants">
                                <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                                <item><hi rend="italic">United States</hi>
                                    <list>
                                        <item>The Secretary</item>
                                        <item>Sen. <persName corresp="#p_GWF1">George</persName></item>
                                        <item><gloss target="#t_Amb1">Amb</gloss>. <persName corresp="#p_WJH1">Whitney</persName></item>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_QDA1">Quarles</persName></item>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MRD1">Murphy</persName></item>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RWM1">Rountree</persName></item>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_ECB1">Elbrick</persName></item>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HJC1">Hagerty</persName></item>
                                        <item>Gen. <persName corresp="#p_GCAJ1">Goodpaster</persName></item>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName>Macomber</persName></item>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_PH1">Phleger</persName></item>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName>Wilkins</persName></item>
                                    </list></item>
                                <item><hi rend="italic">United Kingdom</hi>
                                    <list>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LSJSB1">Selwyn
                                                Lloyd</persName></item>
                                        <item>Sir <persName>Frederick Hoyer Millar</persName></item>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_DPH1">P. H.
                                            Dean</persName></item>
                                        <item>Mr. <persName>Harold Beeley</persName></item>
                                        <item>Sir <persName corresp="#p_CSHA1">Harold
                                                Caccia</persName></item>
                                    </list></item>
                            </list>
                            <p>[Here follow a list of subjects discussed and discussion of item 1:
                                the Communist influence in Africa (for text, see volume XVIII, pages
                                53–56) and items 2–5: the Baghdad Pact; the Tripartite Declaration
                                of 1950; the question of arms supply to the Near East; and Agreed
                                Postions, including guarantees re pipelines, Palestine, Suez, oil
                                study, Aqaba, and Libya (for text, see volume XII, pages
                                466–473.]</p>
                            <p>6. <hi rend="italic">Germany.</hi><persName corresp="#p_LSJSB1">Selwyn Lloyd</persName> noted there was an agreed US and UK
                                position paper on Germany.<note n="2" xml:id="d279fn2"><ref target="#d291">Document 291</ref>.</note></p>
                            <p>7. <hi rend="italic">Communiqué.</hi> The Secretary and <persName corresp="#p_LSJSB1">Selwyn Lloyd</persName> discussed the form
                                of a communiqué. The Secretary said that the President favored a
                                short communiqué. The Secretary feared, however, that its shortness
                                might cause speculation there had been disagreement. He thought the
                                present draft, which seemed long, could be abbreviated. He said he
                                would discuss it further with the President.<note n="3" xml:id="d279fn3">For text of the communiqué issued on March 24,
                                    see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin,</hi> April
                                    8, 1957, pp. 561–562.</note></p>
                        </div>
